[[Category:Urdu]]

Ukrainian dance is believed to have originated out of the religious and cultural beliefs, and social customs, of the early Slavic peoples who lived in what is now Ukraine. In the Twentieth Century, it evolved from a form of social dance into a staged form. A more detailed account of the development of Ukrainian dance can be found on [[w:Ukrainian_dance|Wikipedia]], or in the books listed in [[../Other Resources/]].
== Sections == # [[/Standard Dance Terminology/]] #: This section identifies and defines dance terminology that will be used in describing dance steps. # [[/Ukrainian Dance Music/]] #: This section discusses the music used in performing Ukrainian dance.
{{BookCat}}

== Ukrainian Name of Step or English name of Step == {| border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" ! Ukrainian Name | Enter the Ukrainian name for the step here, as written in the Roman alphabet. If a single step has multiple Ukrainian names, list all of them. |- ! Cyrillic | Enter the name or names of the step as written in the Cyrillic alphabet. |- ! English Name | Enter the English language name for the step. If a single step has multiple English names, list all of them. If Ballet terms are used to describe a step, include them here. |- ! Direction of the Step | Identify if the step is Stationary (performed on one spot), travelling, or turning. |- ! Music | Indicate the number of beats or bars that are used to perform the step, and indicate the count. |- ! Opening Position | Indicate the position of hands and feet at the beginning of the step. |}
=== Description ===
[[Category:Ukrainian Dancing]]

The dance of Central or Eastern Ukraine is frequently referred to as Poltava, after the city located southeast of the capital, Kiev. This region is characterized by wide open land, and the character of the dance reflects the unobstructed landscape. Movements tend to be flowing and horizontal.
== Sections == # [[/Basic and Common Steps/]] #: This section identifies steps that form the foundation of this regional style of dance, and which may be performed by both men and women (boys and girls). # [[/Steps for Men and Boys/]] #: This section identifies steps that are only performed by men and boys. # [[/Steps for Women and Girls/]] #: This section identifies steps that are only performed by women and girls. # [[/Steps for Couples or Groups/]] #: This section identifies steps that require two or more dancers. # [[/Sample Choreography/]] #: This section provides sample choreography which may be used by dance groups wishing to perform a dance that is characteristic of this region.
{{BookCat}}

The dance of Hutzulshchyna is characterized by sharp, vertically oriented steps. Hutzulshchyna is a mountainous region, and the steps reflect the vertical, enclosed landscape.
== Sections == # [[/Basic and Common Steps/]] #: This section identifies steps that form the foundation of this regional style of dance, and which may be performed by both men and women (boys and girls). # [[/Steps for Men and Boys/]] #: This section identifies steps that are only performed by men and boys. # [[/Steps for Women and Girls/]] #: This section identifies steps that are only performed by women and girls. # [[/Steps for Couples or Groups/]] #: This section identifies steps that require two or more dancers. # [[/Sample Choreography/]] #: This section provides sample choreography which may be used by dance groups wishing to perform a dance that is characteristic of this region.
{{BookCat}}

The dance of Bukovyna is quick, lively, and features intricate footwork. It is influenced by the dances of Moldavia, which it borders.
== Sections == # [[/Basic and Common Steps/]] #: This section identifies steps that form the foundation of this regional style of dance, and which may be performed by both men and women (boys and girls). # [[/Steps for Men and Boys/]] #: This section identifies steps that are only performed by men and boys. # [[/Steps for Women and Girls/]] #: This section identifies steps that are only performed by women and girls. # [[/Steps for Couples or Groups/]] #: This section identifies steps that require two or more dancers. # [[/Sample Choreography/]] #: This section provides sample choreography which may be used by dance groups wishing to perform a dance that is characteristic of this region.
{{BookCat}}

Zakarpattia or Transcarpathia is another mountainous region. Movements tend to be vertical and bouncy.
== Sections == # [[/Basic and Common Steps/]] #: This section identifies steps that form the foundation of this regional style of dance, and which may be performed by both men and women (boys and girls). # [[/Steps for Men and Boys/]] #: This section identifies steps that are only performed by men and boys. # [[/Steps for Women and Girls/]] #: This section identifies steps that are only performed by women and girls. # [[/Steps for Couples or Groups/]] #: This section identifies steps that require two or more dancers. # [[/Sample Choreography/]] #: This section provides sample choreography which may be used by dance groups wishing to perform a dance that is characteristic of this region.
{{BookCat}}

The dance of Volyn is characterized by energetic jumping and kicking.
== Sections == # [[/Basic and Common Steps/]] #: This section identifies steps that form the foundation of this regional style of dance, and which may be performed by both men and women (boys and girls). # [[/Steps for Men and Boys/]] #: This section identifies steps that are only performed by men and boys. # [[/Steps for Women and Girls/]] #: This section identifies steps that are only performed by women and girls. # [[/Steps for Couples or Groups/]] #: This section identifies steps that require two or more dancers. # [[/Sample Choreography/]] #: This section provides sample choreography which may be used by dance groups wishing to perform a dance that is characteristic of this region.
{{BookCat}}

Polissia borders Volyn, and the dances share many of the energetic qualities of the Volyn region.
== Sections == # [[/Basic and Common Steps/]] #: This section identifies steps that form the foundation of this regional style of dance, and which may be performed by both men and women (boys and girls). # [[/Steps for Men and Boys/]] #: This section identifies steps that are only performed by men and boys. # [[/Steps for Women and Girls/]] #: This section identifies steps that are only performed by women and girls. # [[/Steps for Couples or Groups/]] #: This section identifies steps that require two or more dancers. # [[/Sample Choreography/]] #: This section provides sample choreography which may be used by dance groups wishing to perform a dance that is characteristic of this region.
{{BookCat}}

'''Announcing: Communicating on Broadcast Media'''  is an open-content textbook on the profession of announcing.  It is a free online book anyone can read, write, or edit.

Broadly defined, announcing is the professional practice of vocally communicating messages to an audience through broadcast media.  Those who practice this profession are called [[w:Announcer|announcers]], although most announcers prefer to use a more descriptive title to describe what they do.  Some announcers work in radio as "disk jockeys," radio journalists or program hosts.  Some announcers work in television as newscasters, sportscasters or "booth announcers."  Some announcers are [[w:voice acting|voice actors]] who specialize in doing commercial "voice overs," narrating documentaries or providing voices for animated films.  Still other announcers communicate using public address systems, such as those found at sports stadiums, racing tracks and "disco" nightclubs.  Although there are many different kinds of announcers, a common thread through all of these occupations is the central importance of using one's voice to effectively communicate a message.

